{'nid': '405391', 'title': '<a href="/history-programs/niels-bohr-library/oral-histories/44668-1" hreflang="en">Victor Reis</a>', 'field_interview_abstract': "<p>In this two-part interview, David Zierler, Oral Historian for AIP, interviews Victor Reis, formerly of the Department of Energy.\xa0In part I, Reis recounts his childhood in New York City, his education at Brooklyn Tech, his undergraduate experience at Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute (RPI), his enrollment in the Army Reserve Officers' Training Corps (ROTC), and his graduate work in electrical engineering at Yale University, where his dissertation focused on supersonic flow. Reis describes his work at the Ames Research Center where he focused on aeronautics, his work on missile systems with the Anti-Missile Research Advisory Council (AMRAC), and his decision to join Lincoln Laboratory at Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT). Reis explains his research on space lasers, and the factors leading to his decision to join the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy. Reis provides a broad view of science policy in Washington, his consulting work at Science Applications International Corp. (SAIC), and his work at Deputy Director of Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA). In the final portion of the first interview, Reis discusses his work as the Assistant Secretary of Energy for the Department of Energy Defense Program.\xa0</p>\n", 'field_additional_persons': '', 'field_audio_excerpt': '', 'field_bib_number': '44668-1', 'field_catalog_record': '<a href="https://libserv.aip.org/ipac20/ipac.jsp?uri=link%3D3100014~%21148916~%213100001~%213100002&amp;aspect=subtab232&amp;menu=search&amp;ri=5&amp;source=~%21horizon&amp;term=Reis%2C%20Victor%20H.&amp;index=PAUTHOR">See catalog record for this interview. </a>', 'field_has_audio_excerpt': 'No', 'field_institutions': '', 'field_interview_date': '', 'field_multiple_dates': 'April 7, and April 22, 2020', 'field_interviewer': 'David Zierler', 'field_interviewee_image': '', 'field_interviewee_image_2': '', 'field_interviewee_image_2_credit': '<p>Credit unknown.</p>\n', 'field_interviewee_name': 'Reis, Victor H.', 'field_interview_location': 'Teleconference', 'field_image_name_authority': '', 'field_preferred_citation': '<p>In footnotes or endnotes please cite AIP interviews like this:</p>\n<p>Interview of Victor Reis by David Zierler&nbsp;on 2020 April 7 and April 22,Niels Bohr Library &amp; Archives, American Institute of Physics,College Park, MD USA,<a href="http://www.aip.org/history-programs/niels-bohr-library/oral-histories/44668-1">www.aip.org/history-programs/niels-bohr-library/oral-histories/44668-1</a></p>\n<p>For multiple citations, "AIP" is the preferred abbreviation for the location.</p>\n', 'field_related_audio': '', 'field_related_images': '', 'field_single_or_first_session': 'First in a multi-session', 'field_subjects': '', 'body': '<div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden">\n<div class="field-items">\n<div class="field-item even" property="content:encoded">\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>OK. It is April 7th, 2020. This is David Zierler, oral historian for the American Institute of Physics. It is my great pleasure to be here virtually because of the coronavirus crisis with Victor Reis. Mr. Reis, thank you so much for being with me today.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Pleasure to be here.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>OK. So for starters, can you tell me your current job title and your affiliation?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Right. I\'m retired. I retired from the DOE just about three years ago.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>OK. And some institutional affiliations that you\'ve kept up in the interim?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, when you say institutions, you mean since I\'ve retired?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yes.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. I\'ve been over at Institute for Defense Analyses. I still have friends around—I\'ve talked to the people at the Sandia, Livermore a couple times, given talks there. I gave a talk at RAND Corporation. And I\'ve been mostly working on my book and then discussing various things that would show up. I\'ve been doing things virtually actually before this—doing interviews, it\'s just a lot easier to do this stuff. And the technology has really come along pretty well.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>It has. So you\'re well positioned for our current moment?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I think so.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, I\'m looking forward to it.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>OK. Great. So we\'re going to start right at the very beginning. Tell us about your birthplace and your early childhood.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Oh, my goodness. Let\'s see, I was—you don\'t give me out a Nobel Prize when this is done, that\'s…</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh] No promises.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, I was born in New York City, and I can\'t actually verify this, but the first year of my life we lived right behind Yankee Stadium, and it was only two stories at the time. And my father claimed that we would go up on the weekends and watch Joe DiMaggio and so forth play, and see Babe Ruth play from behind there. We moved out to Queens, so I lived briefly in Elmhurst. We lived in Jackson Heights, is where I was growing up. And I went to—[coughing] pardon me. You might be seeing the coronavirus in real time.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>I hope not.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>You never know.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>I hope not.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Right. I guess I went to—ended up at a school called The Red School House in Manhattan. We lived in Jackson Heights, so I took the subway every day from the time I was 10 years old. But then I went to Brooklyn Technical High School.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I must tell you that I\'m writing—as I say, I\'m writing a sort of semi-memoir and that Brooklyn Tech really sticks out as a very thoughtful, strategic-oriented place. I went there starting \'49, graduated in \'53. You still had a lot of returning veterans from World War II who had been there before World War II. It was still post-depression World War, and New York City at the time was very vibrant technically. And so, as I\'m thinking back, again, and looking at various institutions I\'ve been to, Brooklyn Tech really stands out now as an important—they knew what they were doing.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. My father-in-law went to Brooklyn Tech. I\'ve heard many amazing—</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Oh!</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>—stories about it.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>That\'s right, that\'s right. I\'m sure he\'s younger than I, so, yeah. Well, it\'s interesting. I\'d taken the—in New York City—where are you from?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>I\'m from Upstate New York. My parents are from Brooklyn.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Oh, OK. So there were three big high schools at the time, Brooklyn Tech, Stuyvesant, and Bronx High School. To get in you take a test. It\'s the only thing that mattered. I took the test, I got into both of them, but the subway trip was less to Brooklyn Tech.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now, were your parents native New Yorkers?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yes, they were. They were both native New Yorkers.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>What did your father do for a living?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>My father was a dental mechanic.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>You don\'t see them quite as much. They made false teeth. At the time, it was much more prevalent. A lot of people had false teeth, and so he was the one who made the false teeth for the dentists. Dentists made the impression, gave it to him, then he took over from there.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And your mom, did she work outside the home?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>No. She was a homemaker. She worked briefly as a cashier at a local hamburger joint. Wonderful hamburgers, but the fryer went on fire once and that ended that.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And your parents emphasized the importance of education, I take it?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. You know, typical Jewish parents. It was sort of assumed.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>They never said, well, you should do this or that. I had started out at PS 69, which was down the block, and wasn\'t doing very well. And that\'s when they put me into Elisabeth Irwin\'s Little Red School House, which was sort of a left-wing, progressive, but a very, very well—again, oriented towards teaching.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now, entering Brooklyn Tech—</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>—were you already expressing an interest in the sciences and science policy?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, again, it seemed like a natural thing to do.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I can\'t think of any one moment when it—oh, gee, I want to be one of these.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>In retrospect, my second son, when he was 12 years old, said what he wants to do is put up big buildings in New York City, and that\'s what he\'s doing.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And he\'s the vice president for technical stuff at a great big real estate development corporation right now. And he always wanted—he went to MIT, studied construction. That\'s what he wanted to do. But I don\'t remember exactly when I said, gee, I want to be an engineer. My father, because he was in the dental business, said, "Well, you could be a dentist." And he was quite obviously more than friendly with the half a dozen or so dentists he worked for. But, somehow or other, it just seemed like—just did it.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>I wonder, late \'40s, early \'50s, how large did the Cold War loom in your consciousness or at Brooklyn Tech from an engineering and science perspective?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It didn\'t—it was the Korean War at the time and that was more on people\'s mind, but I didn\'t really put the two together. It was something that, you know, it was going to be there. I remember in a chemistry experiment, we did some little explosion and the teacher said, "Well, this is not Korea, now, so we can\'t—watch out." But it was not—in Brooklyn Tech, even the social studies was very intense —social studies expected us to read the New York Times every day.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I mean, that was all basically part of it. But I can say that the Cold War didn\'t really show up—[coughing] pardon me—\'til I got to college. I went to RPI as an undergraduate, and there I was in—[coughing], pardon me— ROTC, so it was part of the background. But it certainly was the major part of my whole career.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right, right. Now, you graduate Brooklyn Tech in 1953?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Right. Pardon my—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>No. Go ahead. Take your time.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Just have a little bit of a—[coughing] pardon me. Yeah, \'53.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And, at this point, were you choosing a college on the basis of your interest in engineering?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. And I took the—in New York City, I guess they—maybe they still do it, because I had something called Regents Scholarship.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Again, it\'s an exam that everybody in the city takes, or a lot of people took. If you got it, you got, like, $800 a year, but you had to go to school in New York State.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So there were some good engineering—I mean, Cornell was—but that was five years.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So I figured, well—I knew I had enough money for about a year or so, so I didn\'t want to take that chance. So that left RPI, Brooklyn Poly, but Brooklyn Poly was one additional subway station. So I figured, well, I\'ll like to get out.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So I just applied to RPI and one other school, whose name escapes me right now, in Upstate New York. But RPI was essentially it—that\'s why I ended up going there.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Did you have a good experience at RPI?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, again, I\'m writing this up now and it\'s turning out, you know, it wasn\'t really that great. The head of the ME department didn\'t believe in the second law of thermodynamics. It didn\'t really come together. But I was a co-op student and—I was a co-op student at GE in Schenectady. It was the works, a big—they were coming together after World War II. They had done a lot in World War II. So it was the works. And co-op students—RPI did a co-op program where you did your first two years in a year and a half, and then you went to work for a semester at a company and then came back. So you were sort of out of sync with your class. But GE, at the time, had a rather extensive program where, when people would go to work for them right after college in engineering, they would send them around and they would spend three or four months at various places. And this was testing gas turbines. Not aircraft gas turbines, but large gas turbines at the time. And so you were thrown in with a lot of new graduates, even though you were just a sophomore. And, of course, it was great. I worked at night. There was always a lot of pressure to do the testing. These were enthusiastic kids. They were kids really, but young men, 22, 23, 24. I think the foreman or the guy who was running it must have been 25. He\'d have been there for a couple of years and so forth. So it was a wonderful spirit of trying to get this stuff out in time. It a big tactical—this was sort of the overlap, if you will, of the industrial—industry, and the digital world had not come in yet.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>People still used slide rules.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>You probably don\'t even have a slide rule.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>I do not.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. Do you even know what a slide rule is?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>I do. I do know what a slide rule is. I’m probably the last of the generation to know what that is, but I\'m aware of what is, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Going back just a bit at Brooklyn Tech, every room had a slide rule, a great big huge slide rule in the front of it over the blackboard.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yep, yep.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So you did slide rules. And, of course, again, going back, now, since I\'m writing about that—well, we did two years of drafting. You could learn how to draft in ink on velum. That was really unusual. So I learned how to do that. But you also had an extensive shop experience. You did wood shop and then you went to the foundry and then you went to the machine shop. And then you took your own stuff with you as went through it, so you had practical experience in it. They had a wonderful program called Industrial Process. We would learn how mills worked and Bessemer steel and so forth. So it was all designed to come together. Thinking back, it was a much more well-organized place. And New York, at the time, after World War II, manufacturing was there.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So there was a natural flow. And everybody at this school came to school on the subways, so you integrated in with the transportation system. Again, you had some good—Brooklyn Poly and NYU and Columbia. You had a number of very good engineering schools. So, at that time and place, it was a very thoughtful technical approach.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now, at RPI, was there a humanities component to the education or it\'s all math and science all the time?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>There might\'ve been. I don\'t remember it.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh] OK.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It would be, one, because you were the—if it was, it didn\'t stick.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right. And what are you thinking when you\'re graduating? Are you thinking you want to go to grad school right away, or how did the opportunity at Yale come about?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. Well, one thing, I got married. My wife and I eloped at the end of our junior year. So, because I was in ROTC, the local person in ROTC told me the army will give you a year. So I was just looking around for a school that I could get a masters in one year.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh, uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And I\'d heard one of the professors said, "Hey, I\'ve been to Yale and, you can do it in a year. You don\'t need a thesis." So that\'s why we went to Yale. I applied to Yale, Princeton, and Columbia and I got into all of them, but Yale, one year guaranteed, so that\'s why I went.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Going from ROTC, did you ever flirt with military service?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Not really</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh, uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So I went to Yale—after I was there a year, they asked me to stay on and get a—they had a PhD program and they asked me to stay on. So I checked and then, no, I had been told wrong information. I actually—as long as you\'re a fulltime graduate student you were registered in the Ready Reserve, but the army would continue to defer you as long as you were fulltime, so that\'s what I sort of basically did. Now, back to the—to try to answer your question—I never did really consider—when I finally got out of graduate school, I went from Yale to Princeton, where I got my PhD. Then I did go in the service, and I did the training at Fort Knox, running around learning how to be a soldier. But then the army sent me NASA, N-A-S-A as we called it at the time, out at Ames.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So I served my Army time \'cause at the time, again—you may remember the Apollo program?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yep.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Despite Berlin crises and everything else, Apollo was really considered the highest priority.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And so NASA would take people from the services, if they were in a combat branch, which I was, and have them serve their time at NASA, which is what I did. But I never considered a military career after, even though, again, I was in the reserve.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now, your degree at Yale, your masters at Yale, was it in engineering?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. Mechanical engineering. And then, what it turns out—again, I\'ve just finished writing this. That\'s why I happen to remember all this. They really didn\'t have much of a PhD program. In fact, I don\'t even think they had any PhD students at the time. And they sort of left you on your own. And after a year beyond getting my masters—everything went fine. I did actually take a physics course —every year all the new physics students have a whole year of essentially classical physics. I took that and I actually enjoyed it. But, clearly, they didn\'t have much of a PhD program. So I went on my own, I went to Grumman Aircraft on Long Island.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm. Was this before it was Northrop Grumman?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yes. It was really Grumman, and it was still very much a World War II corporation but they had grown. Engineers didn\'t sit in front of computer screens or computers, but everybody in huge bullpens filled with drafting tables. That\'s where you did your thing. So you had your slide rule, maybe a mechanical calculator, but mostly you had a T-square. It was mostly drawing.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And your PhD at Princeton was also in mechanical engineering?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yes. What had happened was they were just starting a program in mechanical and chemical engineering about doing a supersonic molecular beam, where the mechanical engineering was mainly fluid dynamics. With a molecular beam, I can study chemical reactions, surface reactions, additional things like that. So they were just starting. Again, this gives you more information you probably want to know. But the people that I met—the people at Grumman were just getting into high-altitude fluid dynamics in the research department. They had a consultant who came and talked to them, pointed out to me—his name was Coleman Dupont Donaldson, named after Coleman Dupont , who was his grandfather, who was the president of the DuPont Corporation.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Wonderful aerodynamics guy. He said, "Why don\'t you go down to Princeton and talk to them because they\'re starting this program." So I went down to Princeton and then I thought, oh, this will be good. I\'ll somehow work out a deal with Yale, but Yale wasn’t interested, so I ended up switching to Princeton and I got my PhD there.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And what was your dissertation on?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It was on supersonic flow —I built a little wind tunnel where I studied the flow of gases out of a very small, teeny little nozzle. And you got gas exhausting essentially into a vacuum. So I had to build a vacuum chamber and probes and all that sort of stuff.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And what was the contribution? What did you see as your contribution with this work?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. I found a rather obscure paper which gave all the theory that I was able to verify. And then I used different gases, and it turns out that it had a shockwave in front of the probe, it changed the distribution. They ended up building the supersonic molecular beam eventually. This was just to understand some of the physics. My thesis advisor, John Fenn subsequently won a Nobel Prize for that stuff in chemistry, as opposed to in physics. Now, the interesting thing looking ahead is that my thesis advisor—I was his first student, John Fenn. And he said, “We can use that shock wave to separate uranium." It turns out later that the South Africans used different aerodynamic procedures from that.</p>\n<p>So, again, as I\'m writing my book I\'m looking for connections in terms of people, in terms of ideas. Which, as you\'re talking to people, I\'m sure, you run into all sorts of connection of people who worked together in this area. They show up later in their careers. They remember each other. They tie in. Some of the sort of intellectual connections, as well as, then—so there\'s a network of ideas as well as a network of people. And I\'m trying to basically go into some of that. When you\'re all done, you might want to think about—I\'m sure you\'re doing oral histories of a lot of different people—how do they connect, as well as just what they are.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right. That\'s right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. That could be really an interesting thing.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>That\'s right, that\'s right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>So you saw this work, because of the insight of your advisor, that there was a nuclear energy component to your research?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I didn\'t see it, he did.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. But it never went anywhere—we ended up with a patent on this thing, but, by that time, I had moved along. I didn\'t see it.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I\'d would like to tell you, wow, I saw this 50 years in the future I\'m going to be worried about that. Didn\'t happen.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>So you defend in 1962, and what\'s your next move from there?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, that\'s when the army—that\'s when the army sent me to NASA, Ames Research Center.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. So what was the arrangement? They sent you there as an army—</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>—as a civilian or as a uniformed employee?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, as military —but you didn\'t wear a uniform.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Originally, I was going to be signed up for two years. Of course, that was the standard time. But it turns out my PhD took me five years to get. All that time, I was in the Ready Reserve. The rules said, well, if you\'re in the Ready Reserve for a certain length of time, you don\'t have to go in for two years, you can go in for six months. So what I had done was—and I didn\'t know this at the time. I thought, we\'re going to go in for two years. But I graduated in June. The army, they give you a course you run through for six weeks to make you a trained officer. That didn\'t start until September. So I started out as a civilian and then switched to a military officer. OK. Same job doing the same thing. And then I switched back again to a civilian. But nobody knew that—you couldn\'t tell the difference.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So I can\'t say I did very much in the military —as I say, my only military career in the military was if you will, six weeks of training at Fort Knox.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now, what were some of the big projects going on at Ames at this time?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, again, I\'m really—that part I\'m writing about. Ames was original NACA, the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics. In fact, everybody there talked of it—nobody talked of it as NASA.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It was N-A-S-A.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And it was primarily wind tunnels. That\'s where a lot of the high-speed wind tunnels had been done. They were still doing that. The group I was in, we were in ballistic ranges where you fired pellets at very high speed using a two- stage light gas gun. In fact, we were firing them into a flow behind a shockwave, from a shocktube which came in the other direction. NASA Ames was very instrumental in the manned space—the reentry part. By the time I got there, even though that was 1962, the reentry problem had pretty—I mean, it was there but it was vague. But the reentry problem had pretty much been solved, but you were still going ahead with the—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Solved on an experimental basis or a theoretical basis?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Mostly experimental. It was big experiments. You know, it was big wind tunnels. They did some plasma jets. Ames was a very hierarchal institution. So you really didn\'t know what people in other branches were really doing. Going back—kind of a cultural, I wouldn\'t say tension, but Ames had not really joined the space program. Ames was still dominated by the aero stuff. And they had the world\'s best wind tunnels. And they did some calculations, some boundary layers, some things like that. They had a very super-low-turbulence tunnel. They had high-speed tunnels. They had one, the big tunnel, 40 feet by 80 feet, a great big tunnel. So it was dominated by big machines, big experimental machines and aerodynamics. There was a group also that built funny type of airplanes, and for some reason or other they had put some bio stuff there, as well. But it was not—NASA was dominated by Apollo at the time, and Apollo was dominated, if you will, by Houston, Huntsville. So you were working on a second tier of their big program. And I ended up doing spectroscopy of the shock layer which was kind of interesting work.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But it was science stuff, publishing in the <i>Journal of Quantitative Spectroscopy and Radiative Transfer</i>.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And you understood the endpoint of your work was directed entirely towards the space program? It did not have a military component or a national security component?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>No. It didn\'t have the military component at all.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But what you\'re asking is an interesting thing, because I was there two or three years—I was doing science in a place that wasn’t really scientific. And, secondly, I really began to realize that I was not a scientist. I was measuring—I had learned how, using the spectroscopy in the shock layer—it was really kind of interesting, but I was measuring electronic oscillator strengths, f numbers, as they called it. I don\'t know how much of a background you are, but it\'s sort of molecular physics. Well, wait a minute, is this the space program? Not exactly. I did get a call once from Max Faget at Houston saying, "Are we [Apollo] going to have a problem?"</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I said, "I don\'t think so." And that was it.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And also, it was really not all that satisfying. I remember talking to a colleague who was at, at that time, Cornell, and he was also measuring these f numbers. And he said, "Vic, what does your gut tell you?" And I realized my gut didn\'t tell me anything.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>His gut told him something, yeah, this is too high or too low or something like that. Wait a minute, there are these people, these scientists who are real—I was doing science, but these were scientists who had this feeling, OK, sort of not just what the data would show, but the data meant something to them in a different way. You probably have people—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>You probably understand that. And I said I didn\'t have that.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure. I wonder if, at this point, you were developing an appetite for policy, though? Is that something that\'s happening at this point?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>No, I didn\'t really understand the policy stuff, actually, \'til much later when I found myself in the Office of Science and Technology policy. I was doing it, but I didn\'t call it that.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>What happened is one day we got a visit from a guy from DARPA. It was ARPA, at the time, probably. But he told us what they were doing and why he thought some of the work that we were doing at Ames was of interest to them. And he was part of their ballistic missile defense program. And I said, wait a minute, I felt that I would be a lot more useful in ballistic missile defense than manned space. So that\'s when I left NASA Ames to go to General Motors Defense Research Laboratory.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now this would have been 1964?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>That would have been, \'65, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And what was the location of the research center?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, NASA\'s was at Ames, Moffett Field.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>This is was in Santa Barbara.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And, again, GMDRL had a terrific group of guys. They had built also some very large ballistic ranges. And Santa Barbara is a very nice—Goleta, actually. Santa Barbara is sort of a nice area. And they hired people from Ames out who had built some of these guns at Ames. They could pay them more. They brought in people from the Army Ballistic Range Laboratory out here in Maryland. They got a whole group from Canada. They even got a guy from South Africa. And they sort of pooled all this together. And they really got some good stuff. Now, of course, if you go to Google, you don\'t even find this place anymore. And I remember asking them, "Well, why is General Motors doing this?" I mean, you\'re curious, right? And I never got an answer for that except when people said, General Motors made more money in World War II, which is true, than any other corporation. They made engines and tanks—they really did a wonderful job. Right after the war, they got out of it and went back to civilian production —of course, the profit margins making cars are bigger than military. Apparently GM was very concerned about being broken up by antitrust.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>On what basis? They had competitors.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>They were pretty strong at the time, and they were afraid that the government would take away Chevrolet, make them separate—now, I don\'t know whether this is true or not. This was the story. And the way they figured part of their strategy was work for the government. Now, originally, they hired a guy to put all this together who said, "Well, we can take away Polaris from Lockheed," or something like that. Of course, he got sick, and the guy who became head of it had previously been head of the Cleveland tank plant. OK. Gee, defense, this fits, right? They were not going to be doing that anymore. And his first job was, well, let\'s get rid of the library. Why do we need a library? You know what I mean?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>An interesting part of BMD research at the time was there something called the AMRAC, Antimissile Research Advisory Council. Have you run into that yet?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, I have.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. It was terrific. I mean, the whole ballistic missile defense was run like an academic enterprise —we had two conferences a year. They had a journal, the classified <i>Journal of Ballistic Missile Defense</i>, which became the <i>Journal of Defense Research</i>, which was peer reviewed with an editorial board. So it was run like, I don\'t know, the American Institute of Physics or something.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Somehow or other connected with this, if you will, quasi-academic group with some of the best physicists in the world—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now, you\'re working in a—is this a classified environment? Are you working with a security clearance—</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>—at this point?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Oh, yeah, yeah. This became very classified, right.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Where did you first get your clearance? Was it with the army? Was it with Ames?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It was actually at Ames. I wasn’t aware of it, because when Cliff McLain from ARPA came and gave us this talk, the branch chief said, "All you people have secret clearances," without ever having—I mean, you have to always fill out a lot of forms anyway, right?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But there was not a—57B or something like that.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I don\'t remember. But I had a clearance. So this is all classified. The AMRAC meetings were classified. We\'ll get into that later, maybe, how the roll of clearances and secrecy is very important.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. And most of your colleagues at Santa Barbara, they had physics backgrounds or mostly mechanical engineers?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>There were a lot of physicists. The guy I worked with, in fact, had gotten a PhD in physics. Princeton, at the time, I was very—actually, in the physics department, they were doing a lot of shock tube work.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And what was the basic divide—I mean, what kind of work were physicists doing in Santa Barbara as opposed to what kind of work engineers were doing? Were they working hand in hand? Were they working on separate projects?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, the group that I was with, again, were pretty much based around the ballistic range work. And so they were doing—I mean, it\'s understanding the fluid dynamics of high-speed wakes and turbulence and Navier-Stokes and all that, et cetera. Is that physics or engineering? I mean, it\'s sort of at the blend</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And, again, this whole idea of the antimissile, antiballistic—it was ABM in those days—drew in a lot of genuine physicists to work on that program. I mean, Hans Bethe was there giving a talk.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>The RAND Corporation had a whole big thing, called it the physics department. Albert Latter and so forth and so on. And people looked at all sorts of astrophysics and things like that, so it was certainly physics—by the time you got to radars and missiles flying around, it was engineering. Same way with the space program.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But there were physicists doing engineering, or was it engineering doing a little physics. So it was at that juncture. And this was this problem which ballistic missiles—gee, the Russians—I mean, it were pretty serious at the time.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>What was the sort of like understanding of the Soviet threat at this time? What was the urgency to improve the US missile capability vis-à-vis the Soviets?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Oh, well, it was the Cold War. I mean, it really dominated. They were the—it was the enemy by that time.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Certainly, it was pretty clear, even when I was in the ROTC summer camp or whatever, they were very straightforward about that, that the Soviets are the enemy and that sort of thing. And they were doing the same thing we were. I\'m sure you\'ve done a fair—there\'s a lot of literature on that.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>We\'ll get to that—it\'s only quarter after 10:00. But, when I ended up many years later with the Comprehensive Test-Ban Treaty, that was part of the goal, was to talk to the Russians.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And it was after the Cold War.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah. And so how long were you in Santa Barbara?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, again, three years.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Because I realized, wait a minute, I\'m the—what we were doing is trying to use these ballistic ranges and detailed measurements to understand fluid mechanics, the radiation—that\'s the part that I was doing—and from a high-speed flow into the wakes. But then there was all the radar stuff. The same time, the big player was Bell Labs.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And their main contractor in the understanding optical radiation was a company called Avco-Everett Research Corporation. And they were doing measurements. In addition to laboratory measurements with shock tubes, they had done a lot of the shock tube work. They were also measuring the ballistic missiles coming in at Kwajalein in the Marshall Islands. And so, after that, I said, well, I wanted to get closer to where the—if you will, the actual events—and so I moved to Avco-Everett.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Which was in Everett, Mass.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh, uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And the director at that time was Arthur Kantrowitz. Has he shown up yet?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>No, not yet.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>OK. Well, he had been a professor at Cornell academics, but he had done supersonic—he had worked on molecular beams, as well. Serious guy. You\'ve got Google, you could look him up. So he thought he could—the reentry problem was considered the big problem. And he said, well, he can solve it using shock tubes, and he did. I mean, it wasn\'t him, but he hired all these graduate students of his.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>These were serious physicists, now, right?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Doing shock tubes and then he also had a very classified program, which I didn\'t find out until later, about building lasers, carbon dioxide lasers, magnetohydrodynamics using—again, he put together a wonderful team of people. Interesting, again, since what I\'m studying is trying to understand its organizations. It was run by committees. There was no organization.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It was all done by the fluid dynamics committee and the radiation committee and so forth. And anybody could go to any committee meeting you wanted to.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And you did. But the only thing was Arthur was at the head of the table and ran the meeting, and it was very academic, and people argued back and forth. I mean, it was just like a—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And this was also run under a military contract?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Right. You had a big—DARPA.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>OK. You had a DARPA contract, and the contract I worked for was as a big subcontract for Bell Labs who was doing the main ballistic missile defense for the Army, and also for the air force, reentry observations. So that was, again—even the AMRAC meeting, antimissile research, it also included in the air force. So, right from the start, I think people were looking at both sides. And, at some stage, I began to realize that it\'s the offensive guys that are going to win.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>What made you come to that conclusion?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Again, thinking back, there was—you couldn\'t make ballistic missile defense work. But I remember very specifically one problem we worked on—if you\'re looking at defending your own radar, OK, you would shoot up a defensive missile. It was a nuclear missile. It would go off, then you\'d be blinded for a while. Then the other missile, "boom." The next one—you\'d kill one, the next one would come through. And I remember listening to a paper that was from Bell Labs. I don\'t know if it was at an AMRAC meeting or not. It was, is it better to ladder up or ladder down? With some really fancy mathematics that goes along with that. I said, Vic, this is not for you. I mean, is it really a difference whether you ladder up or ladder down? You\'re now working on a edge of a problem that the basic problem can\'t be solved. So I said let\'s think about—so began to slowly move in the other—you asked about policy. Well, that begins to say, wait a minute, what\'s our policy with respect to this?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Not just, well, can we do it. Wait a minute. Does it make sense to do it?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right, right. And are you working directly with people at the air force and at DARPA, or you\'re not at that level yet?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I\'m sort of at that level. I\'m sort of getting there. You would get visitors coming out—Santa Barbara\'s a nice place to visit. Somebody had to take them out for lunch or dinner.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I volunteered.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And so I got to know people, academics and whatever, and they began to talk to me as colleagues, plans and whatever. And so I began to move up, and the data was getting interesting and you were beginning to get into a community. And there were some pretty substantial people working in that area.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And they would treat you like—not like an underling. You were aware that they were interested in your opinion.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Which is, of course, to some degree, at some stage, you sort of get that. And I just felt, again, that the missile defensive work and moving to Avco, where you had all these people who were really, really good —they were good at General Motors, as well. They\'re even better at Avco. And you began to integrate with some of the really best minds. I remember Steve Weinberg.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I mean, I\'ve run into him subsequently where he would—they would have seminars every two weeks. It would be just like an academic department And that lasted for about another three years. At that point, a fellow named John Penhune was starting his own company and he asked me to join him, because I had, at that point, began to move from just doing experimental work—I began to get interested in doing systems analysis. And one of the things I did at Avco was these—they said, well, let\'s do a system analysis —when we\'re doing all these measurements, let\'s see how we can put them together in a system. And I ended up doing that, and I was really very interested in that.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And, in fact, even at the AMRAC meetings—there were two meetings per year . One meeting was concentrating on the technology, the other meeting was concentrating on the systems stuff. And I began to just get interested in basically doing systems. That\'s when computers were coming along, as well, and I was able to use BASIC.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>There were special groups who could use large computers and I did it once and I said, "I\'m spending all my time with Hollerith statements. What the hell is that?" You know what I mean.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It was not—two equations to solve, but I needed a huge amount of—so I didn\'t want to—I let somebody else basically do that. But you were getting to the point where you could sit on a time shared machine and basically do your own sort of calculations. I said, "Oh, I could earn a living basically doing this." And there were also these people who thought about systems, how things fit together, and that sort of captured me. And so with Penhune we went off, started a company doing that. It was part of a—the whole thing was a subsidiary of a company called General Research Company. You probably can\'t find that. Started off by two people from DARPA who left DARPA, Ben Alexander and somebody else. They were in Santa Barbara, so I knew them. They started this company. They could sell stuff to DARPA as well as, they could end up profitable. What I learned from that was I really wasn\'t terribly interested in business, either, hiring people, firing people, balance sheets. I mean, that\'s not that it\'s—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Not for you?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Not for me. And we did all right.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And what years would this have been, late \'60s?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>This would\'ve been, like, \'69.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>OK.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>\'69, \'70, \'71.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>OK, OK.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>All right. And then I moved from there to Lincoln Laboratory.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Was it a successful venture? Did you make money?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. I made $3000.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>OK.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>You know what I mean. I didn\'t lose any money, right? I made $3000, right? I owned 4% of the company, so 1000 per percent.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But I did realize, wait a minute, I like doing the analysis a lot and I have a skill at it. I could see a problem and I could put it into simple terms. OK. And then I could—I was using HP-35. Enough things were coming along you could do it at either using a slide rule but also using a hand calculator, you could do a little bit of programming. It wasn\'t very hard if you thought about it.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So then I went to work for Lincoln Laboratory at the time.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now, I wonder, Vic, at this point, with the Nixon administration and SALT and all of the nuclear détentes diplomacy—</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>—how much of this is actually affecting your work on a day-to-day basis?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Right. Not much. It was kind of interesting because ballistic missile defense was one of the big issues, right? Should we have one, should we not?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right, right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And my feeling was, well, let\'s do more R and D \'cause there was a lot of interesting R and D to be done. But once it gets deployed, the deployment didn\'t make—I had been getting involved in the systems analysis that the deployment really didn\'t make sense if there\'s one ballistic missile coming you can get it. If there\'s two, you probably can get it. If there\'s ten, that becomes too hard.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And I began to realize that. So do you want to spend the rest of your life doing that? And the answer was, well, not really. It was pretty straightforward.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Are you spending any time in Washington at this point when you\'re with the company?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, yeah. Because they\'re the customers.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It was DDR&amp;E and DARPA were our main customers. It was kind of interesting because, if I move back just a little bit, I\'ve decided to leave Santa Barbara, but I ended up—there was a fellow who was the head of the physics department. It was the physics department at UC Santa Barbara, Herb Broida.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And he said, "Vic, would you be interested in going to work directly for DARPA as a program manager —" And I said, "Well, whatever." And then I got a call from the DARPA people and they said, "Look, we have done a search, we\'ve looked at everybody and you\'re top of the list. Could you come to work and help us with BMD?" And I had accepted the job at Avco the day before and I just would feel funny about one day accepting a job and the next day calling them back and saying—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>—and do that. And they tried to twist my arm and they said, "No, Kantrowitz would love it." I mean, I just didn\'t feel right about that. They said, "OK. We\'ll go to the next guy on the list." The next guy on the list was Kent Kresa. Now, Kent then went to DARPA, went to Northrop and, as you know, became president of Northrop.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So we became friendly, and I remember telling him, "If I\'d have gotten a call a day earlier, I\'d be the president of Grumman right now."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And he said, "Well, I\'m not sure you didn\'t have the better deal."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But part of that also, again, is the is this interweaving of events and people and how they flow. People you met early in your career show up again later. You maybe stay friends with them or whatever. You end up being their boss or they end up being your boss, and it flows in and out. That\'s what Eisenhower meant when he said, you got to watch out in this dangerous scientific technical—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. Yep.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. All right. Well, let\'s see. So I moved to Lincoln Laboratory.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now, what was the connection to MIT? How did that play out?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, MIT is Lincoln Laboratory.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right. But what was your connection to Lincoln Laboratory? Were you recruited there?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I was a staff member. I worked in the Optics Division and then the Director’s Office as Senior Staff. And I was there for almost 10 years.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But I had a different role at MIT. I ended up being a one-man systems analyst—helping people at DARPA and DDR&amp;E. They would call up when they\'ve got this problem or that problem and so forth. A lot of it was lasers and space object identification. And somehow I fell into this role of not getting integrated into the structure of MIT, but working for these people in the Defense Department at pretty high levels, director of DARPA, where he\'d say, "Go help one of my program managers and get this organized. Help them think about getting it organized." But I also began to work pretty closely, again, with the directors of the laboratory. And subsequently I realized, well, wait a minute, this is not just analysis, but it also gets involved in strategic planning and that sort of thing. And so, even though I was in the Optics Division at Lincoln over time I was doing so much of this that—helping my people at DARPA and DDR&amp;E, that Lincoln just put me on the, literally, buildings and grounds. Then I also got pulled into study groups. The missile defense or cruise missiles and so forth, they would have big study groups, and I was sort of the designated representative, if you will, basically to help. And then, I got involved very much in terms of when DARPA wanted to do big lasers.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Lasers in space and all that kind of stuff. So I became interested in that and realized that, wait a minute, lasers in space and BMD did not fit together particularly well. And, by that time, it was getting serious overlap. And I was helping my friends in the Defense Department fight that off by using analysis. And DARPA—it was George Heilmeier, was the director—asked me to work directly with one of his people.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>For example, one example was they had something called space object identification. The Russians were putting up a lot of satellites. Well, what is in them? Well, you can listen to their telemetry and so forth, but could you image them?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Could you look at the radar? And so Heilmeier asked me, "Look, we got about 20 programs." Literally, there were 20 programs. "Which of our programs are ready to be transferred to the Air Force or somebody who do it operationally? Which of those that still look promising, or which of those that maybe we can get rid of it? How do you do that?"</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So, "Why don\'t you work with the program manager, figure that out." \'Cause DARPA, you do programs for some length of time and then you get out.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now, I wonder, Vic, at this point your vantagepoint with DARPA, was your sense that everything that they were involved in had an obvious military component to it, or were they—they were not involved in any research for purely academic purposes?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, we\'ll get to that later, when I become the director of DARPA—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>—and the Cold War ends. On the other hand, looking back, I mean, there were people there who were academics.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I mean one decade\'s just purely academic becomes next year\'s military.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And that\'s really a—I think you could make a real contribution when you talk to people and then put that together.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>\'Cause the theme of my book, now that I\'ve started writing it, is, wait a minute, how does that tension between policy and science show up?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And Eisenhower is saying, "Wait a minute, these scientists don\'t know anything about statecraft. They\'re taking over." And Feynman saying, "Yeah, you\'re a scientist. You have to maintain your scientific integrity."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yep, yep.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And how does that tension come together, and then, how do different policies play into that? And so that\'s the theme of my book. I\'m beginning to do that stuff at DARPA.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right, right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But my role at—I\'m at Lincoln, but I\'m the guy who they come to to say, hey, how do I think about this problem? How do I make that decision on DARPA\'s programs?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Are you rising up in the ranks at Lincoln Laboratory? Are you a staff member the whole time?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>No, I did not want to rise through the ranks, \'cause rising through the ranks meant management of people.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So I created my own job, which meant you—at Lincoln, I became a senior staff person. They didn\'t have much of that. I mean, you could be a scientist, but this is somebody who was at that junction, should we be doing this, should we not?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And what I tried to do when I was at Lincoln, I would not try to get involved with what I now realize is the policy part. And people would say, "Well, what do you really think? Is this a good idea or not a good idea?" I said, "That\'s not my job. My job is to do the analysis, without a policy recommendation, if you will. Look at all the data—do the calculation, turn it over to you and you figure it out."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>So who was the decider?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, it was, for example, the director at DARPA. All right. Let\'s see. We\'re now almost—I want to be sure we get to the—in fact, we could come back and talk more about this. But, for example, I had a friend of mine who was the DARPA program manager and he was doing krypton excimer radiation, lasers. That\'s what he was doing. And they were very large, you could project—they were going to be large and heavy. And Heilmeier, who was the director said, "Well, this is never going to have any military application, therefore we\'re going to cancel your program." So he told me—Greg Canavan calls me up and says, "Hey, can you figure out how—let\'s get together—he\'s going to kill this by the end of a couple weeks, the end of the year. Will you figure out a way to make it work ?" So I came down to Washington, with my little HP-35, I said, "Well, look, suppose we put the laser on the ground and put the mirror in space and give you your numbers." And the mirrors were huge. And I said, "This is really stupid, but that\'s what the numbers say —" Oh, he gave it to Heilmeyer —he loved it.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I said, "Wait a minute. At this stage, just doing the analysis is not quite good enough. You would like to be able to say something about the utility —"</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>They started a whole program. So I said, well, wait a minute. At some stage, I got to start saying whether this makes sense or doesn\'t make sense. And that\'s when the laser ballistic missile defense started playing in. DARPA asked me to take a look at all their lasers and which ones you could turn over to the services. And you realize, well, this doesn\'t make any sense at all. And that\'s when some of my friends at DDR&amp;E said, "Look, could you help us? Because that\'s going to come waving in here and that\'s going to be a big deal. And so could you do the analysis or help us guide the analysis to show that that\'s really a stupid idea?" And I did. And, of course, having done that at Lincoln, that\'s when I got the job at OSTP based on my background and having done all that.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And this was a political appointment or a civilian job?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Political appointment.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>OK.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I mean, it didn\'t take confirmation —but you work in the White House, I\'d been doing this for some 8, 10 years or something. That was sort of a job I had worked out for myself, and had worked it for friends at DDR&amp;E, a lot of at DARPA, air force. When people needed sort of a one-man check, they would come and ask me to think about it—spend some time. But I would try to put numbers into things, not just scratch my head and say, well, it seems to be whatever.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>So who actually hired you at OSTP?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Jay Keyworth.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh, uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And this is going to be a major part of my story, because I\'d been at Lincoln now 10 years, but even though I was at Lincoln, I was primarily spending my time in Washington doing these analyses, primarily lasers. And I\'d only met him once because he was head of the physics department in Los Alamos.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And he called me, we met, and he came to Boston to see me. I was at Lincoln Laboratory. And he said, "Look," he said, "People don\'t know this yet, but I\'m going to be President Reagan\'s science advisor."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yep, yep.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And there\'s a lot on that, and you can probably read about.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure, sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And he said, "I\'m thinking of maybe—would you like to come down and be head of national security?" And I said, "Well, I don\'t know." He said, "How would you think about it?" I said, "I think it\'s pretty simple." I said, "Right now with Weinberger there\'s going to be a lot in the Defense Department and nobody\'s going to worry about everything will be good. There\'ll be a lot of money." I said, "But there are going to be some things that are so stupid, that are going to annoy the Defense Department. They\'re going to go directly to the White House. So you\'re going to need somebody in the White House to be able to stop that." And I said, "That\'s probably going to happen in about a year."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right. Now—</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And he said, "It\'s happening now, come to work." And I did.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. Now, OSTP is a relatively new office. It was only formed in 1976. And so I\'m curious if your sense is that—was it a new place because of Reagan\'s election? Would it have been a very different place had Carter been reelected?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, I knew the person who was the OSTP director under Carter —I got to Frank Press, and I knew Frank—but I didn\'t know very much about the office at all.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It was a fairly substantial office in Carter, but Carter also, remember, was an engineer, so he did a lot of that stuff himself. I got to know—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure. And a micromanager extraordinaire, as well.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yes, absolutely. Since I was at Lincoln Laboratory, MIT, Frank Press was an MIT professor, so I talked to Frank about it. And Frank said, "It would be a wonderful job. Take it. It\'s great. You can get a place in Washington, do a couple years. It\'s got to be a good thing to do." So I was not—I didn\'t vote for Reagan, but Keyworth, said, "We\'re being pressed at all times by a lot of this laser stuff and a lot of this stuff." And from his perspective lasers BMD made no sense at all. "So why don\'t you come, and that\'s your job to—you can come right away." And I didn\'t know from Washington at all.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I mean, my Washington experience had been with DDR&amp;E and DARPA, which is very technical.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right, right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And you probably looked up—there\'s a lot of good literature, which I am now reading back on this stuff. Reagan didn\'t want to bother with a science advisor at all.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But it was in the law, and it wasn\'t worth going around. And so, six months later—and it\'s not clear to me whether it was still—going back, whether it was Edward Teller or some group of businessmen, Bob Hunter\'s brother\'s buddies, who got—went to Reagan and say, "Well, why don\'t you have a science advisor?" And then, why was it Keyworth. Keyworth\'s story is that, well, Reagan\'s daughter, Patti Davis, was a problem. He wanted somebody younger to talk to Patti Davis. And what you learn is that there are all these sort of random events which are not necessarily logical, but flow over time—the decisions are made. I mean, if I didn\'t bump into Keyworth in Los Alamos while I was fighting off lasers for my friends in the Defense Department, he would not have put two and two together and asked me there.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>\'Cause, while I had been going back to Washington frequently, I\'d never had a Washington job really and didn\'t understand the Washington culture particularly, except the narrow DDR&amp;E, DARPA type.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And it\'s not the same thing as the policy guys.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Right? So I went to work for OSTP. And now that I\'m looking back at OSTP, I mean, it\'s a major chapter in the book—I don\'t know if you\'ve read Kistiakowsky\'s book?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Wonderful.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I mean, I\'ve read it subsequently. There\'s also another book, a professor—I could find it for you—of Eisenhower\'s perspective on that.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Also great. One thing to look back on it and say, wait a minute, now I understand some of these things, or at least have a framework for understanding how you get all these things.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>So what is your role in the flow of information? What\'s coming to you and what are you passing on from your desk?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, what\'s interesting is that, because you\'re in the White House and you\'re this system director or whatever, you can get any information you want, almost. The first time I\'d heard about the National Security Agency—I mean, I\'d heard about it. I worked actually at a higher-level clearance for some special programs at DARPA. But, hey, I could pick up the phone and call the deputy director of CIA or the director of NSA.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I could call any—you get the view of everything if you ask. And some people even call you ahead of time, because you don\'t know what the role is of the Science Advisor is —I mean, Kistiakowsky was very important, as was Killian and Wiesner. These were important players.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And you\'re in the White House and you get driven by a car somewhere. So the information flows—any kind of information flows in. So when I was asked, "What is your job?" I said, "Well, my job is all like strategic astrology."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>OK. The pseudoscience charts had this great-big planets, all of them orbiting around, and when they come into conjunction. I said, "Well, I\'ve got great-big planets too. I\'ve got the air force, I\'ve got CIA. They\'re moving in their own—I can see what\'s happening and I can nudge them a little bit and I can put them into phase. And six months from now they\'re going to come into phase, and I can call a meeting six months from now, they\'ll all come, and they\'ll get something done." So you really asked the right question. So as far as the information coming in, it\'s anything you want.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Now, what do you do with it?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Well, so on that question, what are you looking for? You can find out any information you want. How are you not getting overloaded? What are you prioritizing in terms of what you want to know?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, a couple things happened. All right. So you\'re there. There was no one—Kistiakowsky, if you read his book, was pals with Eisenhower. Eisenhower really cared about it. Keyworth did not report to Reagan, he reported to Ed Meese, who didn\'t have an operations job, either.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>He was just a counselor. I was that position with Keyworth, one level down, so I was staff to staff to staff. But since you\'re in the White House, people don\'t know how these things flow.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And I\'m pretty aggressive, so I tried to use that uncertainty. And the reason I was hired was, in fact—\'cause Keyworth hired me, he says, "Wait a minute, Reis has been doing all this work for DARPA and the DDR&amp;E, and so he\'s got all his buddies, air force—" I could go more into that, navy, et cetera, et cetera. "So this is another channel, OK, that he has." And when you\'re working in the White House, especially, that\'s where we learned all about stealth, we learned all about ASW, we learned all about whatever. And you\'d catch up. And the people at OMB know where all these things are going. So you\'re in a staff position, so you say, well, what\'s your agenda? Now, it turned out that Jay\'s agenda—Jay did have an agenda. He was to improve science.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>He was real—I mean, Jay was a little nutty in some respects, but he really did care—the thing he cared about was A, science, and B, using science to help Reagan win the Cold War. OK. Those are the two. But he took the idea of being the science advisor, that you represent the science community. And Reagan—this is not a lot of scientists in the White House. This is not Jimmy Carter.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But Reagan was susceptible to all this stuff.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And Jay said, "I\'m going to try to help him do this." Jay\'s agenda was to increase the budget for the National Science Foundation. Looking back at when—that was probably his highest agenda.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Why do you think? What was it about the NSF?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, because that represents science.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And he wanted to show that the, one, he believed in it. And particularly, even though he worked in a laboratory, he was the head of the physics division there, and a lot of that was academic science. And even though he was not particularly beloved in the academic science community, he felt that that was his—I would say that was his number one agenda.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And so, well, whether it was the Cold War or using science for the Cold War or whatever. And I was not part of the NSF. But it became clear to me that that\'s what he really cared about. He was not particularly articulate about it, but that\'s what he really cared about. And that is something that a science advisor—I mean, that\'s part of their job.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>They get rated on—and the specifics of how do you represent that in the NSF budget.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>If the NSF budget goes up, the science advisor must have done a good job.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And it may be simplistic, but there\'s some substance involved in that. That isn’t just symbolic. So that\'s what he really cared about, and he was not doing it from a very strong position. He was not a strong academic scientist like a Frank Press was, or some of the things we were in. For example, he recreated what was then called the White House Science Council as opposed to the President\'s Science Council.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But that\'s really what a science advisor is really all about.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So you get to know all these people.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yep.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And so you really asked an extraordinarily important question, how did you get your information and then where did it go? The problem was most of it was a shunt to zero.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And you had to figure out where it went, and it wasn\'t obvious. Because it was not a logical place where one put that—OSTP was just sort of a bastard child—and there were 10 people there when I got there.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And it\'s not like with Obama where you\'re talking about 150 people.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>What\'s the natural flow from OSTP? Is it going through the NSC?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>When I was there, it was really OMB, and to some degree NSC. Because of my job, I went to all of the NSC—part of my job was to go to all of the NSC staff meetings. But that\'s also a very good question. It was primarily, however, with OMB, \'cause OMB had not a bad technical group.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Wait. Vic, I\'m sorry to interrupt. It\'s hard to hear with the background talking.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>All right. They\'re giving—I\'m living in an old age home, so they—senior residence community. They\'re making some announcement.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>We can wait \'til it\'s over.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>All right. They\'re explaining—they\'re always setting up new rules, right, because of the pandemic.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Are you at Five Star, by any chance?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Oh, OK.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. No. I\'m at Five—why, do you—you\'re not at—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>I know it well. My wife\'s grandmother was at Five Star for a long time.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>OK. What\'s her name?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Jean Greenspan.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>All right. Well, no. We tend to know just people by their—we\'ve been there three years. She doesn\'t have to worry—they\'re really doing a nice job.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. How long has she been there?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Oh, gosh. She got there in—I want to say 2011, something like that.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Oh, yeah. So she\'s been there a long—we can\'t see each other anymore.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right, right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>So everyone\'s eating in their apartments now? Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Everyone eats in their apartments. All the programs have closed. I still go out for a walk, which they let you do. When you come back, they take your temperature.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. No, it\'s—well, that\'s another story.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>All right. I think we can go back in now. It seems like it\'s stopped.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>All right. OK. So where were we?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>So we were talking about OMB and you\'re a staff member. You\'re—</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>OMB was—I\'m trying to think of the science guy. And there was a—who you might\'ve run into who\'s dead, \'cause most of the people are dead. But I was impressed with the OMB people. They knew their job. They really did more than just do the budget. I don\'t know where they are now, but this was early 1980s. They were professional people. You helped shape the OMB. I think that was—yeah. NSC was less so. The NSC those days was Ollie North—I mean, it was a group. I got to be friendly with—you\'d go to a meeting every day and—but the real interaction was OMB.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And that was on a staff-to-staff basis. And most of the time, since they were instrumental in putting the policy—that\'s where the policy and the budget come together. Then you would basically work with OMB.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now, leaving in 1983, are you thinking of this as a short-term appointment or had you left—</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, I got there in \'81.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And I thought of it, more or less, as a short-term appointment—as a whatever. \'82-1/2, Jay asked me, "Why don\'t you see if you could stay longer?" Why didn\'t I become the deputy director of OSTP. But then Star Wars happened.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Now, we were hired to stop Star Wars, Jay—and we were doing that. But then Star Wars occurred. There\'s a whole lot of books that describe that.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>They\'re by and large accurate. You don\'t get the days and date, but that\'s when Jay and I split, and that\'s when I\'m saying, wait a minute, what Feynman told you—there\'s a line you really don\'t want to draw. And that\'s when I left OSTP. But leaving, you quit but you have to work at—I mean, that\'s what all they people in Trump—how do you quit in some sort of—there are ways you do this.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>You know what I mean.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But that was the first opportunity I had, then, again, to show that, wait a minute, you\'re going to have this, let\'s say Feynman moment—we had been working on a speech for—Jay had been working on a speech for—a defense speech for Reagan. But what Jay thought it ought to be is stealth, which was a black program at the time. So one of the things I learned a lot about was stealth while I was in the White House.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Not that they—they were eager to tell it. Jay said, "Oh, that\'s what we want to have the president give a speech about." Well, the president decides to give a speech, but it is not what we want him to give a speech about, or what Jay wanted him to speak about. It was just the reverse. And Jay said, "Well, the president wants it so let\'s do it." I said, "Maybe you can do it. I can\'t."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>OK. But I don\'t want to start the anti-SDI group. I\'ll just not work on—I\'ll leave and not work on it. So that\'s the, if you will—that\'s where the policy and science clash, if you will—the science in this case isn’t all that complicated. It\'s back to the BMD problem, right? The earth is round. I don\'t know who—Archimedes or somebody figured that out. That was all the science you really need. Most of the time, you\'re not where you want to be.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But Jay said, "No. That\'s what the president wants, therefore we\'ll say we can do it." And I said, "The president may want it, but your job is to say you can\'t do it, or we\'ll try our best but—"</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>It\'s not happening.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>"—it ain\'t gonna happen." And so then I broke with—so I left that and I went to work for SAIC. Now, the other thing relating to the policy at OSTP is that Reagan wanted to have a space policy, or the people around him did OK. And OSTP was going to bring in somebody to do the space policy, but they didn\'t. And they\'d already decided the space policy, at least the working groups and all that, would be running through OSTP. So Jay said, "Why don\'t you do space policy?" And what do I know from space policy? But I learned.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And so we did a space policy, as well. And that\'s all covered. I don\'t know if you know John Logsdon.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, his book is actually a good result of that. But that\'s when you suddenly realize, wait a minute, there were all these people in Washington who actually did something called policy.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>That\'s all they do.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>They go to meetings and they think about it. And well, that\'s what I—I wrote equations and solved them or helped my sponsors—but I was doing policy, I just didn\'t recognize that\'s what I was sort of basically doing. But there it was, the whole OSTP and the space policy. In our space policy, Jay was the scientist, and the big issue was—there were a couple issues. One was the—should there be a space station. NASA was pushing the space station, of course. Second was should the air force and the scientific—the other community, any community really, be forced to go on the shuttle.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Should we keep launchers, rockets, separate, you know, launch it, or should everything be on the shuttle? And the third was, what you had indicated earlier, was the business of doing space for military purposes or space for civilian—so it all sort of came together. In the meantime, at the time, a big player in space was the National Reconnaissance Office, NRO, which it still makes me feel funny to mention that, because even the words were classified at the time. We didn\'t admit the organization existed. And yet, a lot of the most important space programs were, in fact, classified. I mean, the Hubble telescope is nothing more than one of those—instead of looking it down, you turn it over, and look at—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>—and so forth. And then there was manned space versus unmanned space. That\'s where NASA came in. Well, wait a minute, I left that manned space stuff back at NASA many years ago. So I had to basically pool all that—and then there was, well, wait a minute, shouldn\'t there be a space council? How do you make those decisions? Are they made in the White House? That\'s where the civilian program, NASA, and the military program come together. How do you—well, wait a minute, that\'s done in meetings of people and councils. And which council gets involved in—so this is all relatively new to me. Basically, how do you figure all of that out? So, then again, you also got the SDI.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>You know, this is what the Star Wars stuff—well, that\'s the space program.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And then you have underneath is—then you have the thing we were pushing, which was, wait a minute, stealth is coming along which can make major changes, but that\'s still a black program.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>How do you decide—at which point do you make that—and it\'s a pretty big—it\'s a big deal. So all of these things come together. And you have the president\'s science adviser, who\'s not advising the president at all.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>He\'s advising somebody who\'s also advising the president.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right, right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And you\'re advising him.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And then, you\'re connected—on the other hand, you\'ve got these people in the rest of the world and the government who said, "This guy works for the White House. He must—" I was there no more than two or three days, I got this call from Edward Teller saying, "You gotta talk to the president and you gotta take all this classified stuff and unclassify it."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh. How did you get that call?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, he knew I was working for—I don\'t know how. I mean, previously he had told Canavan, who was—you remember I told you at DARPA when I started working with him. I talked to Teller, and Teller said, "You shouldn\'t talk to Reis. He\'s devious."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But he called me up. He says, "Well, you\'re in the White House, right?"</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>"You\'re in the official phone book, therefore you must—you\'re science advisor, national security. You must be in with Reagan with every two days?"</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So they don\'t know. All right. So, in that case, I called a friend of mine, a person who had been working with the intelligence community. "Oh," he says, "You got the Teller call? Every time there\'s a new administration change he\'ll call and say we have to change our whole classification system." And remember, by the way, which was interesting on this—that\'s, again, in my book—is that why do I call the dangerous elite—Eisenhower\'s farewell speech where he said, "Watch out for these scientific guys."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>He was specifically talking about Teller.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh, uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Who was fighting the CTBT, Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, which Eisenhower wanted.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, we\'re probably going to get to this later, but when I ended up going to work in the Department of Energy, I ended up running stockpile stewardship, which has to do with Comprehensive Test-Ban Treaty. So it\'s all these, if you will, webs. You the webs are not just people, but they\'re—you got that fourth dimension of time, how they connect up with time. And the person who was pushing manned space when I was doing space policy was Hans Mark.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Hans had been secretary of the air force when I was doing some work for them—when he was secretary of the air force back when I was working with DRR&amp;E on different problems entirely. He ends up at NASA. He subsequently becomes DDR&amp;E. I had been to DDR&amp;E. So all these things basically—I\'m not sure how I will connect them, but there is that connection; and how does it flow in and out? So, in addition to, wait a minute, there have been intersection between science and policy. That\'s why, when you\'re all done, you can write this up. It\'s going to be important.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>That\'s right. So who was your connection at SAIC? How did that come about?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, let\'s see. So I\'m at the—I\'m doing this policy stuff, right, at the OSTP. I have a break with—I\'m going to leave. I\'m not going to support SDI. One of the people who was close to Jay who was on the White House Science Council was a fellow named Ed Frieman.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Have you met—he passed away recently, but he—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>No.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>—was, in fact—Ed was head of the Plasma Physics Laboratory at Princeton.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>He was in the DOE Office of Science. He ran the office of science at one time. At the time I met him, he was on the White House Science Council and we became friends. And he had worked for—he at the time was also chief scientist at SAIC.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And, in fact, I remember telling my wife when I was leaving, I don\'t know what I was going to do, but I certainly would not go to a place like SAIC. So Frieman said, "Well, why don\'t you talk to Bob Beyster?" who was the president of SAIC—have dinner. And I said, "Why waste time with somebody—" He said, "Go ahead, give him a—help me, \'cause that\'s what he does."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Frieman was sort of right? So I had dinner with Beyster, and Beyster said to me, "Well, I\'ve got this company, SAIC." Are you familiar with it at all, how it works?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>At the time, it was all employee owned.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>OK.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And it\'s a whole \'nother story in my book - employee owned. And he said, "I\'d like you to be head of—my board of directors is after me to put together some strategic planning. We don\'t have a—so why don\'t you come to work for us, and you can be head of strategic planning?" I didn\'t even know what strategic planning was —he said, "You\'ve been in the White House. You must understand this strategic planning."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>There was no—you know what I mean.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, that might be interesting. And then I got a call from Larry Lynn, who\'s the deputy directory of DARPA.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And he said, "We\'re trying to put together a counter-stealth program. And I put my best guy on it—best program manager. We just can\'t get it started. Could you come and help us do that, and could you go to work for SAIC, \'cause they\'re one of our—" see. So I went to work for SAIC. So it was a combination of Freeman—I had also been working—I had also gotten quite friendly at the time, very friendly, with a fellow named Gene Fubini.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Eugene Fubini. You run into Gene at all in your—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>I\'ve heard the name.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. He was a student of—he was Italian. His father was a professor. He was a student of Fermi\'s in Italy, came to this country after he graduated, and ended up—again, another big story. But he and I were friends. He said, "You should go to work for SAIC," as well. "I\'m on their advisory panel." I talked to Bobby Inman, who was deputy head of CIA. He said, "Well, he\'s going to be on the board of directors." So it all seemed to play, so that\'s when I worked for SAI.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And you were out in Reston or they had a D.C. office?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>No. They have offices all over, but I was out in Tysons Corner.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>OK. And so I read a book on strategic planning, right?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh] And now you\'re an expert on strategic planning?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. Company came—and, in fact, I had been doing it, but I hadn\'t realized that that\'s exactly what I was doing.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>It\'s a fancy title for what you had already been doing.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It turns out, again, in retrospect—and I took it very seriously and tried to understand the—and now that I\'m looking back, I\'m realizing that Beyster actually had a very good strategic plan, but he didn\'t have anybody doing it with a title.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And the board of directors, which included not just Bobby Inman but Bill Perry, Mel Laird, I mean there was really a powerful board and they —said, you\'re growing, you\'re getting much bigger, and you need a strategic plan, so he wanted to hire somebody to just take the board of directors off his back.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh, uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And I worked at the White House, therefore, they said, well, this guy knows how to do all that. So I went and worked at SAIC—but, in retrospect, as I said, they had a strategic plan, but they just needed a front—I never had any organization. I did it all by myself. And because I left—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And in what context did they mean "strategic planning"? As in, like, US national security strategic planning or business strategic planning?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Business strategic planning.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>OK.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>All right. It was all employee owned—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>—as I would tell anybody. And the way it operated at the time when I started was everybody ran their own business and they were paid in stock. But only employees could own the stock.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>That\'s a whole \'nother story. You wouldn\'t want—there were groups and branches, and there was all—but it was engaged in the stock. And I went back to him and told him the plan was simple and everybody ran their own business. And if the business failed, they got fired. If they got fired, they had to sell their stock back to the company. Well, who was the company? The employees at SAIC.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And it just sort of grew that way. And after some three or four months, I read a book, strategic planning, ran around and talked to anybody, and they said, "Bob—" I said, "The thing that everybody\'s concerned about is you. There\'s no successor." That\'s the strategic problem.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And he said, "Vic, I won\'t—" He says, "You can do anything, but you can\'t do that."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>He said, "Because I\'ve got eight groups. Each of them—they\'re all doing very well. They each think they can be my successor, and soon as I name one the others are just going to leave. I mean, as I told everybody—people said, "Well, what is this strategic plan?" I said, "It\'s pretty simple. The good news is nobody can tell you what to do."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I said, "The bad news, you can\'t tell anybody else what to do."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I said, "The third thing is, don\'t fuck with Bob Beyster."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Because he controlled this thing in a very nice—in a nice way, but he controlled everything.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It was all based on him. And that\'s what SAIC—I mean, eventually, the board threw him out, I think 20 years later, \'cause he was 80-some-odd-years old. But he could never name a successor.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And the strategic planning was pretty straightforward.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And everybody sort of understood it, but the board of directors didn\'t quite get it, and they needed somebody to be able to—so that was—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>So are you operating mostly outside of national security policy at this point?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>No. It\'s primarily—at the time, I was the—most of Beyster\'s—most of their work was for national security.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>They did some energy stuff, as well. This was in the mid \'80s, so it was the Cold War. Most of it was national security.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And it was mostly Pentagon contracts?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, yeah. A lot of Pentagon—a lot of Defense Nuclear Agency, a lot of nuclear stuff.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yep.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>A little national, but mostly—they began to get work in the National Institute of Health. They work at the level that says we\'re support contractors and we can support Andy Marshall at the high level or just run around and do things and whatever. And it was all based on getting a competitive contract.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And it worked fairly well. It just didn\'t scale up to one guy running it.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It was very hard for it to scale. I also got involved on a number of advisory panels at the time. The defense science board, but also I ran a classified panel for the navy. I was on the—there was a wonderful study that NASA did on space systems, looking at the earth, space system science, where you got involved with the science community —Francis Bretherton put it together. It\'s still around. Well, how do we think about earth science as a system science?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. That was a very good—terrific study. The director of central intelligence had a science advisory policy which was really first rate. It had folks like —Josh Lederberg, Nobel-Prize-winning-class scientist. That\'s what I said. I\'ve worked with a lot of these guys. So about a third of my time was on this panel stuff I started getting involved in, and some of them were actually quite good giving advice to the government. So those navy panels, as I say, was stealth and counter stealth stuff. You couldn\'t even say you were on it —but it had people like—Bill Anders, who was the astronaut who I\'d gotten to know at OSTP. He was then president of General Dynamics. Jim Roche, who was then at Northrop, became secretary of the air force. A lot of serious panel stuff. And SAI said, hey that\'s fine. It flows in. And I also ran a technical advisory panel to SAIC, which was chaired by Harold Brown, former Secretary of Defense —Gene Fubini, Bill Perry who then became secretary of defense, Bobby Inman, John Deutch etc.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So part of my job was to keep them happy, then also keep the board of directors happy. So it was an all-staff position, except for helping putting together this counter-stealth stuff with DARPA. So I did that for about five years or so. OK. And then, I don\'t know how—I can keep talking, but you said you wanted to go to 11:30.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Let\'s keep going.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>OK. But then I was asked by—while I was doing that, I also was working, not just doing the counter-stealth stuff for DARPA, but still ended up helping the DARPA director for the DARPA. And Ray Collady was the director of DARPA.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yep.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I didn\'t get to—when I was at OSTP, we also did an aeronautical study which—Colladay was the NASA guy on the aeronautical study. He was the director of DARPA. He retired and then Craig Fields becomes the director of DARPA. The Cold War ends, right? What do you do now with—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Well, you mean the Berlin wall falls? We\'re talking 1989?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah. In \'89. But it\'s over—you know what I mean.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right, right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Essentially, the Cold War is over.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Craig asks—and Craig had been at the—have you talked to Craig at all?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>I have not, no.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>You might want to try it. I mean, it\'s hard to say what kind of scientist he is, but he\'s a serious scientist. He worked with Jerry Letvin at MIT.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I mean, he\'s one of these real wonder kids.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure, sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But he had gone to DARPA right from MIT. He was the director of DARPA. He asked me to leave SAIC and come and be the deputy director at DARPA. Well, it seemed like an interesting thing to do, so I agree to do that. But I had to go back to MIT for a few months, become an IPA. Are you familiar with IPA?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>No.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Intergovernmental Personnel Act?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>No.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>No. That\'s fairly important. It was originally was put together to allow people from state and local governments to go to work for a year or two in the Defense Department.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>—or the federal agency. It got moved to academic institutions, as well. Then it got moved—sort of the nonprofits are connected with academia. And you would get your real salary, but everybody—so I moved back to MIT—back to Lincoln for a few months to become an IPA, then went in as deputy director. And then Craig—end of the Cold War, he said, "Hey, the threat is not the Russians anymore, it\'s the Japanese."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>You might remember—you\'re probably too young, but people really thought the Japanese were going to be a—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And the battleground is not nuclear weapons, it\'s high-definition television, and the things that relate to that. And you can read all about that. So I come to work as the deputy director. My job as the deputy director—he doesn’t say this explicitly—is more or less to keep things friendly within the Defense Department. Well, he\'s moving DARPA to this essentially civilian—it\'s still called national security but it\'s now—wait a minute, is the national security going to be fought in the marketplace or in the battlefield?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now, were you in the Pentagon, or this is offsite?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>This is DARPA, it\'s offsite—it\'s not in the Pentagon. DARPA has moved to Rosslyn. It subsequently got moved—they\'re now in Ballston.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>In fact, we were in the middle of moving when I went. So I\'m the deputy director, and what is DARPA going to do? Now, having been worked at DARPA many years, I\'ve got a lot of friends in the Pentagon and so forth. Deputy director of DARPA, I\'m there a few months, and I\'m beginning to learn that DARPA is very different than the DARPA I knew, which was working the DARPA defense—part of it.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Ballistic missile defense, cruise missiles, whatever. Oops. DARPA is also supporting this huge academic community, which are doing computers and basic science, none of which I really understood—so the DARPA net was becoming now the internenet, computing, a lot of very basic science. And the professors, they didn\'t care whether it was DARPA or NSF. In fact, DARPA sort of skimmed off the top. I mean, it was a lot easier then. DARPA was competitive but not that competitive.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>In fact, I learned that DARPA really supported four universities pretty much all the time, and then a whole lot of other universities underneath that. So while it looked competitive, it really wasn\'t.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>There was really a dangerous scientific and technical elite which the people working for academia were going through DARPA. That worked fine except that then Craig gets fired.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>What happened?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, it happened—it is well described in a wonderful book which I now have read several times by Sharon Weinberger. <i>The Imagineers: the History of DARPA</i>. There\'s been several—hers is very good, really good. Well, DARPA then actually took a majority—well, not a majority—came on the board of directors, took a stake, an equity stake, in a company that put together gallium arsenide. And one of the competitors complained and Fields got fired.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But Fields really was an absolutely brilliant guy. But getting back to your earlier point, wait a minute, are you investing in military, are you investing in commercial or just science or how does that all—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>—how do you make those decisions? I mean, it\'s really a policy dilemma if you will, an Eisenhower moment. OK. So it was right at that. And Craig got fired, I\'m the deputy director, and so then I become the acting director. Right in the middle of that, there\'s the Gulf War.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So what does DARPA do? It was a high-tech war, and a lot of previous DARPA stuff was engaged. We did some little jobs right in the middle of it. Oh, it was very interesting, as you might expect. So when I became the director of DARPA—acting director—they couldn\'t quite get anybody they wanted and I was doing a good job, so they made me the director. Part of my job, especially the way I got it, the history of DARPA prior to Craig was really pretty much a military, pretty much keeping it secret, classified stuff. Craig moved it—it was now moving, to not so secret. Change the name from ARPA to DARPA and then back to ARPA. And that was a big debate on how much did the government invest in things that, A) are not necessarily military but just basic stuff? Where does that fit in? So that debate really was basically joined, and I didn\'t have to worry about it too much, because I\'m just learning about DARPA. And I didn\'t have a technology that I really loved. There are these people who are really laser guys or really whatever. Remember, I didn\'t have a gut feeling for spectroscopy or whatever. So that didn\'t bother me. It was, we\'re having a war. Let\'s see how we can basically do that. And then, what happened was—and it worked—and the interesting thing about the DARPA experience is when I look at all the stuff, none of which I knew very much about, it just—the hyper-fast computing was really the thing that DARPA ought to be pushing. They had done it, it was starting to come together with massively parallel computing. And I don\'t understand it particular, but these guys really seem to know what they\'re doing. And that\'s what I would sort of push.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now, among the scientists at DARPA at this time, what were some of the dominant fields they were coming from? Was it mostly physicists? Did you have chemists? Do you have biologists? Who were the scientists?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It was mostly physicists, well, computer science. I don\'t know. It was really computer science. The physicists were very strong in material science. There wasn\'t nuclear physicists, I got to meet them, Gell-Mann and these guys would show up, and you\'d chat and that sort of thing. But it was really—the scientists were—more like George Whitesides</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, sure. Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>You know, really good material science. Frequently, however, towards electronics. You know, this is the gallium arsenide, x-ray lithography, et cetera, et cetera. So it was dominated by computer science and the things that relate to that.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And the physics, I think was pretty much materials.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now, your tenure was only a year. That\'s pretty short lived. Did you plan to—</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>—stay on for longer?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, what happened was the DDR&amp;E, what looks like in the charts, in the DARPA reports to the DDR&amp;E, the DDR&amp;E was Charlie Herzfeld.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And he didn\'t do a particularly good job, and he had a particularly annoying personality.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So he was fired.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And they forced me to become the DDR&amp;E.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>This was a promotion or a—</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It looked like a promotion.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>—lateral move?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>No, no. It was a big promotion. It was senate confirmed.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And the DDR&amp;E at one time was really the undersecretary.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Oh, interesting.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>By the time I got the job when they reorganized the defense and named an undersecretary, the DDR&amp;E was now becoming chief scientist to the secretary.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So he was the person who was like the president\'s science advisor. So he didn\'t have a lot of people—it looked like there were thousands, \'cause DARPA reported to him, and the Defense Nuclear Agency reported to him and whatever. Truth is, it was just a staff job.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>In your job—you could tell when the DDR&amp;E was successful if the 6.1 to 6.35 budget went up. It was sort of like the science advisor. The NSF budget went up, he was a successful science advisor. And the specific reason that Herzfeld gets fired, very specifically, was he was asked to put a strategic plan together, with the science and the applied science, for the Defense Department, and he couldn\'t do it. He just couldn\'t do it. Well, wait a minute, I\'m the guy who\'s done strategic planning, so they knew that, and so they made me the DDR&amp;E. And here you are running DARPA, which was really learning this stuff. It\'s hard but it was really a wonderful job. But suddenly you\'re now the staff guy, the science for Dick Cheney.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>You gotta go through the whole procedure, senate confirmation, which is really a drag, a lot of paperwork. And you get involved in all sorts of political stuff that just doesn’t make terribly much sense. I didn\'t want to do that. But I was able to put together a strategic plan, and I did it before I got there. It wasn’t that hard because I now know what it\'s all about. I read the book.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So I learned about how to do this, and then came out and Cheney loved it and Colin Powell loved it. And got IDA to write it all up. And then, this is another area that you—getting late, but, like I say, I can keep talking, but that is really kind of important, is that Cheney said to me—well, he actually asked through Sean O\'Keefe, who was the controller—said, "We really like the strategic plan, but we\'ve got all these laboratories at the end of the Cold War. What the hell do we do with these?"</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>"And we don\'t have to do this in a hurry, but just take some time and come back and tell me—put together a group and tell me what should we do about all those labs, \'cause we\'re spending X-billion dollars, which is a lot of money in those days, on the labs. We\'re not sure whether we\'re getting anything." So we did that study and discovered that the laboratories that were most effective were FFRDCs. You\'re nodding, so I assume you know what that is?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And they were a lot more effective. I said, "Look—" So what we recommended was that you—I mean, Lincoln Lab was an FFRDC, which was working very well. You make the Naval Research Laboratory into an FFRDC. It\'s almost that way anyway. You make a deal with the DOE, Sandia, Livermore, Los Alamos. You\'re putting a lot of money in there anyway. You get them organized as—you pay for them on an institutional basis. You take Wright-Patterson Aeronautical Laboratory, you make that into an FFRDC. And it is important is connect those FFRDCs with universities, same way Lincoln Lab is MIT, Livermore is California. So you connect them in strongly with research universities so you can have consortiums. NRL can work with Virginia, Virginia Tech, Maryland.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>You put that together and then what do you do with the other laboratories? You throw them into the BRAC and let them sink or swim. And Cheney really liked that idea. The service secretaries hated it \'cause it would take away their—service secretaries like to control their own laboratories. And you centralize it, more or less, in the OSD. They can put it together. The military people liked that, as well, but they couldn\'t say so.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, then Bush lost the election, so it never happened.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But the idea of the FFRDC—and the reason they were good was not that they paid more money, but they had additional flexibility. And they had this strong connection with the academic research community. You know, there were scientists talking to scientists, it is this alignment which is important.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So then Bush lost the election, and the new people coming in—well, who are the new people? They\'re the same people I knew anyway. This is John Deutch who\'s on the SAIC Board of Directors. He\'s who I worked with for years- the same group of people, Bill Perry. I talked to you about—so all the new civilian group was the same group I had been working with at SAIC and working—the scientific technical elite back and forth. And I was asked to stay over even though I was in the previous Defense Department. I was asked to stay over—I was DDR&amp;E—asked to stay over. They always ask a few people to stay over through the transition. And I stayed over. Deutch took over the job of the undersecretary. Perry was the deputy secretary. Anita Jones, who\'s also on the Board of Directors of SAIC, became the next DDR&amp;E. But then I ended up with the Department of Energy as the Assistant Secretary for the defense program. And I got that job because nobody would take it, because it looks like they were—well, it\'s the end of the Cold War. President said he wanted to do a CTBT. The budgets were plummeting. Why would anybody want that job? And Hazel O\'Leary, who was the new secretary of energy. The new administration had wanted a undersecretary for science and technology.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And she interviewed me successfully for that job, undersecretary for science and technology.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, look, I had worked at OSTP. I was the DDR&amp;E who ostensibly was the chief scientist of the Defense Department. So the scientist with the DOE—that was a natural, besides nobody would take the job.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But so I interviewed for that. I\'d also interviewed to be Al Gore’s reinventing government initiative —do you remember if you\'re old enough—you don\'t remember—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>I remember him well.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>He was doing this reinventing government.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>With an emphasis on science.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Right. And, in fact, they\'d asked me to come to—they said, "Well, you were DARPA, you know all about computing, therefore you can be in charge of the computing thing. He loves that stuff, and you could do that." And then I was also offered the job of undersecretary of commerce department for technology. So I call up Hazel O\'Leary and said, "Look, I\'ve got three job offers. Make up your mind." Well, I could take any of them, right? So she calls me back and says, "Well, what we\'d like you to do is be assistant secretary for defense programs, nuclear weapons program, and we can offer you that job right now. It\'s Friday. We\'ll announce it Monday." I said, "Fine. Let\'s do that, please." She said, "But you\'ll still be—you\'re still on the short list to be the undersecretary for the Department of Energy. And if we ever get this undersecretary for science and technology, that\'s your job, So I said, "Let\'s go with that. Take me off the short list for undersecretary." So that\'s when I got the job. And, of course, the big thing there was the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Ties you back to the—and that\'s—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And who\'s the driving force in the administration behind this? Is this coming from Gore? Where is this coming from?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Clinton.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>It is coming straight from Clinton?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Absolutely.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>OK. Are you in meetings with him? Are you in the oval office at this level?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>No, no. I\'m in the Department of Energy.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>No. But I\'m saying, when you have meetings, are you having meetings that rise to that level?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>We had one with Clinton.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It\'s the budget meeting, and I went along with Hazel. Panetta was there.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yep. Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Clinton was half an hour late. We all sat around and talked.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But Hazel had figured out this was really what the president wanted.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>The Defense Department was opposed to this. I mean, they wanted to continue to do some—they were saying, well, we\'ll do CTBT later. Let\'s keep on testing.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>For what reason?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>\'Cause they didn\'t think you could do it.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And one of the things, again, is that there was a meeting about, "OK, how many more tests shall we do?" at the White House. I guess NSC advisor at the time said, "Let\'s go ahead do more—we\'ll do another nine tests and then we\'ll stop." And Hazel said, "I\'m the new secretary of energy. I don\'t know anything about this stuff. I don\'t want to vote yes until I understand it." Everybody else said, "No, no, no. You don\'t understand. You\'ve got to vote yes." And Colin Powell, who was then the chairman, said, "No, no. We can\'t let go of this until she\'s comfortable." She said what she would do, we\'d have a meeting and she’d learn about this stuff. Now, by this time, I\'m in this peculiar position where I\'ve been announced as going to be the new assistant secretary of Energy. But I\'m still the DDR&amp;E.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So I go to the next meeting. And, of course, the Defense Department is supporting doing nine more tests. The national security advisor is supporting nine more tests. Hazel really doesn\'t want to do tests because she realized the president really doesn’t want to do that. He likes to make a political statement. He\'s not interested in how secondary\'s work. I mean, he wants to make a political statement and, as part of his campaign promise he said, "Look, I said we would go for a CTBT, this is sort of like—in a way, this is like Reagan saying, "Well, I\'m going to do space."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So I keep my mouth shut during the meeting and then, after the meeting, Hazel comes to me and says, "Vic, why don\'t you write me a memo and tell me what you really think. OK. Just tell me what you think the right thing to do is." So this is my Feynman moment, right?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>At OSTP I had said to Keyworth, you can\'t tell the President we can do defense in space, but he felt he had to support the President—"</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So I sent her a memo. I said, "Look, if you frame this as a scientific program, the ability to maintain—" I said, "I\'m not going to get into the deterrents or any of that stuff. That\'s not my business. But I think we\'re going to have the—we\'re not going to get out of nuclear weapons, right? But the president wants to do it without testing. Suppose you put together a program that says I can think about how I can maintain the nuclear weapons without testing."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I mean, that\'s a very difficult scientific job.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And I said, "If you frame it that way, the laboratory will be able to try it. And I don\'t know whether that would cost more or cost less, but—"</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Who does that satisfy, nuclear weapons without testing? What stakeholders are being satisfied with that arrangement?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>The laboratories.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Even though they opposed it. OK. Because I have framed it as a scientific problem.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Not a national security problem?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, it is a—you said, you gotta do it as—it\'s exactly at the intersection. I\'m going to use science to solve this national security problem, but I\'m not going to do it the easy way. The easy way is to go test it. I\'m going to try to understand it so well, in such detail.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>All right. That\'s a tough problem.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>That is not an easy problem.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right, right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And I challenged the laboratories. And I said, look, now—when I talked to Hazel, I said, "I don\'t know whether this costs more or less." But laboratories said, "Boy, that\'s really hard. We don’t think we can do that. And we certainly can\'t do that without budgets disappearing."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I said, "OK. I\'ll take care of the budget part. You tell me if you think you can do it or not."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I say, "You gotta keep telling me the truth. If you can\'t do it, you gotta say so." But you put your scientific credibility on the line.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>How big of a risk was this?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>At the time, I thought it was about 50/50.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>In fact, I asked people when I went to groups, I said, "Here, let me—" I said, "Suppose we go to the year 2015—" This is 1993. This is around 20 years. I said, "The head of the strategic command who\'s in charge of doing this goes to the president and says, \'Madam President—\' I was joking.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>\'The stockpile is still safe and secure and reliable, and we haven\'t tested for 20 years.\' I said, "What is the probability of something like that happening?"</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And I would have people vote. It was about 50/50. You know what I mean. So I said, well, you know, 50/50, that\'s not bad, right? I mean, you\'re married, right?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, I am.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>How many times?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Just once.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. It\'s a—you know what I mean, then. You win—you know, it seems about right. and then I had a meeting with the weapons guys in the lab. I said, "OK. Let\'s figure out whether we think we can do that. But this has gotta be a science program and you\'ve gotta be able to say whether it works or not." OK. In other words, we\'re going to depend on your scientific—in other words, I\'m taking it way from—I\'m saying the policy decision was made by Clinton. Now, here\'s the science thing: Well, you\'ve got to make a science decision. OK. And you\'ve got to be able to say to the policymakers this works or it doesn’t work. So you can\'t put yourself in a position like Keyworth did on SDI where Keyworth went to Reagan and he said, "You\'re making a policy decision. We don\'t think it would\'ve worked but I\'ll try." He went to Reagan and he said, "This is a policy decision. We will make it work."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>OK. "And we the scientists can do it." And you remember I the March 23rd speech he said, "I\'m turning it over to the scientists and they can do it." And I\'m saying, wait a minute, that\'s not the way science works. OK. Science recognizes you don\'t know the answers until you do the experiment—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right. Sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>That\'s why I said, "Look, we\'re going to—the word stewardship, let\'s call it science based." OK. And I knew the labs—remember, I had just been through FFRDCs and computing and all the things that went with what I\'d done at DARPA and DDR&amp;E. Now I\'m at DOE and, wait a minute, I can turn this problem upside down.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yep.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>OK. And they\'ve done it now. Truth is, part of the reason they were able to —and I had done some back channeling —that the stockpile at the time was actually in good shape.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>There were some issues. I mean, the main issue was, will plutonium last? Nobody knew that.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right, right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>The material science issue—it was a series of material science issues. But nobody knew the answer to that problem.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh, uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But would the Helium bubbles coalesce along in fracture boundaries or not? We just didn\'t know. But there was a reasonable chance that it might work. But I made it into a science question. I put the responsibility to that on the laboratory.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now, Vic, how reliant were you on advances in computer technology at this point? Are you counting on the idea that super computers can reliably serve as a stand-in for testing? And are you coming up with this idea on your own or are you working with colleagues on this?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>No. One, remember, I\'d been at DARPA.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>One thing that occurred to me at DARPA was supercomputing, massively parallel computing, so I knew all that. But I was unable to get the—why we can do the DARPA stuff—I was unable to get the DDR—the Defense Department really was not very enthusiastic about that.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It was too academic for them. So when we started a group of at a big scientific meeting and asked can we do this science-based stockpile stewardship and the group came back and said, "Hey, we think we can do it but we\'re way behind in computing. We don\'t think the computing will be anywhere near enough to be able to determine whether we can do that or not."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>That\'s what I was trying to do at DARPA. So I went and hired, in a peculiar way, Gil Weigand, who had been one of the DARPA program managers. He had been in IPA and at DARPA. He had worked at Sandia—he was leaving—he went back to Sandia, they didn\'t know what to do with him. Difficult personality. So I brought him into the DOE —and I made him into the deputy assistant secretary. And the amount of money that the DOE in the defense program was funding in advanced computing at the time was 10 million dollars.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>They were working on a better RF chip for your ID. That was their idea of advanced computing. So I said, wait a minute, we\'re going to have to improve this by about a factor of a million in ten years. So I hired Gil, and then I said, we need a big company at least to do this like IBM. We got them interested.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>This is a moon shot, I mean, a factor of a million, or this is technologically feasible?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>The JASONs—are you familiar with JASON?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>They wrote a report saying that they liked stockpile stewardship but this was not technically feasible.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It was a moon shot.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But I figured, I mean, what have I got to lose? I don\'t understand this stuff anyway, and there are enough people in the thing—well, we can do all this.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>In fact, this is really a story. But I felt I needed a big computer company to do this who saw a commercial value in massively parallel computing.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And what kind of budget are you working with here if you\'re bringing on a contractor for something like this? Are you really able to authorize a big figure?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>About 80 million dollars. All right? That\'s enough to get the R and D. I wanted to get IBM, so I called Harold Brown. Remember?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>He was on their IBM Board of Directors.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Harold said, "You ought to talk to Nick Donofrio," who was a senior VP, smart guy there. IBM was—I didn\'t know it—IBM was going through some real problems at that time. But they had just brought in Gerstner who, after all, had run Nabisco. He, in turn, was depending upon Donofrio. So I talked to Donofrio. I said, this is what we need. I could never get IBM to participate in massively parallel computing when I was at DARPA. But I got to know the people—you know, you get to—so he said, "Why don\'t you come up and give a presentation, and I\'ll bring the research guys there, and we\'ll meet with Gerstner." OK. So I get up, I give my presentation about what we need to do this. Gerstner says, "Hey, this is big iron. This is IBM. We\'re not in the fucking PC business, we\'re big iron. This is the biggest iron around"</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>He said, "This could be our Apollo program. And he says, "You guys win this contract." He walks out. I knew the computing businesspeople from my DARPA days, and they all came. And then you had to get the labs back. And the problem was, in the labs, the computing was now—had gone to separate groups. And I brought Gil in who really was a wonderful program manager, really did understand it all.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now, IBM is keeping this under wraps? Are their competitors aware of this?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Absolutely. Not under wraps at all.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh, uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>We ended up, however, first getting one—but then we ended up with enough money to be able to buy—trying to think of the other name and the company that won it. So they were competitors. And they had said, well, look, if you do the massively parallel stuff, there may not be a super business for massively parallel, but it comes in modules, so that changes the whole way we think about computing. \'Cause we can sell a lot more at the smaller version.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And it slowly built up. Well, you can see, we made the teraflop by the particular time, and they\'re still going, right? It\'s up to gigaflops now.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Massively parallel really works. And my role in that, I think, was twofold, one, to say let\'s give it a shot, let\'s try. The labs couldn\'t help themselves. Computing was in their blood.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But this put it back into the forefront of what they were thinking about. And they cared about nuclear weapons and there was sort of this alignment of the computing, the science, the nuclear weapons. DOD was very skeptical, but Bill Perry and my friends were there. They sort of trusted me to do that. The key people were the strategic command. And I had actually been on one of their advisory groups and I knew the people—it\'s Defense Department, so I knew these characters. So it was this alignment or—that\'s what I\'m—the book, I was able to align, if you will, Eisenhower and all his things. And Feynman put the science and the policy together, but not let the policy ask the scientists to do something that was scientifically impossible or ridiculous. And you always give the scientists—you guys are now in charge of this, and we\'re going to depend upon you and your scientific integrity. And there will be enough money there to do what you think is correct. It\'s big science. I don\'t know if you saw the paper I wrote on that.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I sort of touch on that sort of stuff. They couldn\'t help—it was the right thing to do, and they couldn\'t help themselves. So the Defense Department more or less went along with it because the president wanted it. He\'s the commander in chief, so they knew that what—they\'re not going to buck him.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And subsequently, I was fired from the job because Bill Richardson came along and felt I was not being personally loyal.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Bill Richardson from New Mexico?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>He became secretary of energy.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It gets into a lot of—this is not policy, this is personalities.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. Yep. But did you leave feeling like you had succeeded in this?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I didn\'t know.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>What state was it at when you left? How far along was it by the time you had left?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It was interesting because it was about—we had gotten the programs going and they were moving along reasonably well. I mean, the problems and the computing in particular was going right along, chugging. Most of the people in the labs were pretty serious about actually getting it done. If you go back and read, the comprehensive test-ban had hearings.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>The laboratory directors were cautiously optimistic, and I think they did it right because we didn\'t know about the plutonium yet. We didn\'t really know whether plutonium was going to—could you use the old plutonium—or would you have to build a new plutonium factory? And there\'s a lot that will go into that, but you\'re probably getting bored by this time.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>My question here is, at the time, did you appreciate the impact that this was having on new generations of supercomputing?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Oh, yeah. Oh, absolutely.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>How? What was your feedback mechanism? Who were you talking to that saw that this was happening in real time?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>The IBM folks.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. And what were they saying?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Well, they said, "We think we can do this. Furthermore, we think this is going to be where computing is going in general."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Now, computing probably went there, but it went into—the other people who I was depending on was Intel, \'cause they were not going to build the computers, but they were going to build a lot of chips.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>The chips, right, right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Right. And these are people I\'d worked with at DARPA and gotten to know. And the IBM, I mentioned to you, I could never get intel to do this. And the academic—remember the maximally parallel was still—was Danny Hillis, and Thinking Machines was still a very important player in this. Feynman, by the way, was working with Hillis. OK.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yep.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So are we going massively parallel? That was still very not clear at all. I frankly, don\'t know enough technically to be able to do that, but I had enough of a sense of the people who were in that. As I say, the Intel guy, Justin Rattner, the IBM guys, and some of the strong people from MIT. There was a guy that had one name, Chuck Seitz at Cal Tech—so there were some pretty powerful individuals —Evans at Utah—there were some pretty powerful people in the academic community who I learned to meet when I was at DARPA, felt that this had a good shot of working.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>So, to get back to the—</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>The IBM people felt it was—and the Intel people felt, hey, we think we can make money on this.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, sure. So to get back to the question, the vantagepoint from 2015—</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>—what is the program going to look like? It makes enough sense how the advances in modeling and simulation were working and that these advancements were possible, but isn’t that still a step removed from knowing if they\'re actually—</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>—going to be testing in the way that actual testing would confirm this?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Furthermore, there was a risk. OK. But I said that the people who—the powerful voice in that discussion was going to be the scientific community.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>All right. So I was not—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Powerful enough—you mean powerful enough to lobby politically? Powerful how?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Powerful enough—well, the person who was most important in this was really Pete Domenici.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And he and I made the—he understood what I was talking about. Not the technical stuff, but he understood the politics of it. And I said, wait a minute, I\'ve got the president wanting to do this. Every president since Eisenhower has wanted to have a comprehensive test ban —it was now the end of the Cold War.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure, sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And, of course, the hard part—we haven\'t talked about this, is when Yeltsin said to Clinton—and I wasn\'t there, but—wait a minute, his people say you can\'t do this without testing. And Clinton said not to worry, we have figured out—and we\'ll show you how to do it.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Uh-huh.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And then he told Bill Perry, "Go tell those people how to do it." And Bill Perry said, "Oh, I\'ll have Ash Carter and Vic Reis go tell them how to do it." And Ash never showed up, so I was the one—and I didn\'t know how it worked myself.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Fortunately, the laboratories had already figured this out themselves. They couldn\'t help themselves going over finding out what the Russians were up to.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And help them figure it out, you know, helping them—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And I assume the Russians\' computer program is, like, way behind, right?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Oh, the one thing we couldn\'t do with them is the computing. But their physics was—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I had several of the Russians tell me you\'re getting us out of the business because you—well, we depend on testing even more than you do.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>So this is really like an elegant off-ramping of the whole arms race, essentially?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>It was an elegant—but it only lasted so long, \'cause Putin comes in and figures, wait a minute—you know, that part.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So it was that sort of moment in time, if you will. We weren\'t sure whether—remember, the Russians were going to be our buddy. And the thing that made the Russians—was the nuclear stuff. And we\'re going right at the heart of that nuclear stuff. How do you work with them? We don\'t have time to discuss this now, but maybe sometime later. But Sieg Hecker has written a whole bunch of books on this kind of stuff.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right, right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But, again, it was—as I\'m thinking about writing the book and everything, it\'s this alignment with these forces underneath these—or these people, and how do you get them together in a certain period of time. So when I was there, I could see an alignment between the laboratories\', strategic command, who were the people who ran the nuclear weapons, and the president. And if you get them aligned, you can get this CTBT.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yep.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Forgetting all the lawyers and diplomats, that would be aligned. And the alignment lasted enough right now. I had one of these TV—I keep calling it television—computer interviews about a month or so ago with Bruce Goodwin from Livermore, who is now going back and saying, well, should we do a CTBT now? Could we do a CTBT now? And he was one of the major players at the time. So I asked him, I said, "How do you think this has worked out?" He said, "It\'s worked better than we had ever anticipated."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And this is five years out from 2015, so there you go.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, right, right. He\'s saying it\'s going to work for at least another full generation beyond the generation that we had thought possible.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>So, Vic, what do you see as the most important legacy of this? Do you see it as a legacy, as victory of peace? Do you see it as an environmental victory? Do you see it as a scientific victory, a computer victory? How do you understand this?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. Well, I think, if I had to go back, I\'d say it really is this combination of—that\'s why I\'m writing the book. It\'s that you come—it\'s the simulation, but it\'s the validated simulation with the big experiment. And ultimately you get back to the scientific technical judgment of the people who are making that decision, and you put them in charge.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>All right. That\'s what Feynman said and we should be doing.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right, right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And it was Eisenhower who said, "Gee, wait a minute, I\'ve got these important state craft things. You gotta watch out for the Edward Tellers."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right, right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>OK. And it was interesting. I had bumped into Teller throughout my career and somebody asked me, "Well, why don\'t you have your picture taken with him?" And, of course, sure. And he signed it, "Vic Reis, thanks for all you\'ve done for the laboratory."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>[laugh]</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I mean that\'s the key, right?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Now, looks Livermore was going to go down the tubes. So I look back, it was—and, again, I\'m writing it—it had to do with this—it was, wait a minute, it wasn\'t science versus policy.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>OK. But how do you do both? I mean, the easy scientific thing was let\'s just continue to test.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right, right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>But if you turned it upside down and made it into a scientific challenge. And you said we are depending upon you to do this national security issue with your scientific institution. Now, the computing, we\'ve given that computing to Google. What happened was they\'re the ones who figured it out.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So, in some ways, the weapons problem is not the big problem anymore.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>I mean, in the sense that that\'s at least good for another generation. Who knows what—so it allows you to do the arms control and it allows you to do deterrence. But, wait a minute, if I go back, presidents really don\'t like that. I mean, that\'s what Reagan wanted—if you read all that stuff about Reagan - I\'ve been going back and reading it. He didn\'t like deterrence.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>None of them do. But you can\'t expect these things to work forever, right? And institutions come and go. We started off by talking about Avco Everett Research Laboratory and all these great scientists. And General Motors—wait a minute, they\'re still building cars. They\'re not building missiles.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Well, Vic, I want to ask—final question is a very broad question. For the past 20 years since you left DOE, you\'ve had a very strong presence in advising government agencies. And your career, it has this Zelig-like quality to it.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, right.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>You always seem to be like right there—</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>—at an auspicious moment—</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>—and in so many different areas and in so many different research endeavors, at the intersection of science and policy. And I wonder, for my final question, if you can sort of survey your career and then think a little bit about how you draw on your experiences in your advisory capacity currently?</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, right. Well, some of the things we didn\'t discuss was where we\'re going now.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Because what I\'ve been spending really the last 15 years, a good deal of it in DOE, even as an advisory position, it really is climate change.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And what I\'ve been working on is the intersection of climate change, nuclear power, and nuclear weapons, because they all connect. And that\'s how I start my book, a letter I\'m writing to Bill Perry, who\'s going to go to zero nuclear weapons . I says, "You know, the problem is maybe you should think about the whole problem."</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Which is think about the whole thing, together. And that\'s what I\'m working—and, frankly, I\'m finishing a paper on nuclear power and the coronavirus pandemic—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>—literally, \'cause well, what else have I got to do —that sort of thing. One is, I have an ability to put things together, and people have called on me to use that ability. And the only place I\'ve actually—I\'ve only run things twice, two or three times. And I\'ve avoided all that management stuff. I mean, Zelig didn\'t run anything, either, right? He never—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, right, right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Sort of showed up. And the ability to figure out, wait a minute, what are we trying to do here, and what are the things that are aligned to do that or not? Space lasers — they just don\'t work. And try to dig through and sort of see that. And there really is, then, a group of science elite, and my role has not been to run anything but, in fact, to do. I didn\'t try to go into the Department of Energy and fix it. I didn\'t try to fix the bureaucracy. I ignored it. And you can see, well, what\'s important and how will you get those people to do something? What are they telling you? And don\'t try to convince them to do something different. They\'re shifting around a little bit so that what they\'re telling you fits the problem. I was asked to come back into the department after I was at SAIC the second time by the the deputy secretary, saying, hey, President Bush—second Bush—wants to do something in nuclear power. And I thought, well, I might know how to put all those pieces together. And it never—I mean, despite the fact that the president, himself, loved it, but it never went anywhere.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>He really loved it, I mean, Bush, the second Bush. It was exactly what he wanted, but it didn\'t go anywhere. Why not? You couldn\'t get people aligned and some of the basic assumptions were wrong. People thought nuclear power was going to be important. Well, it wasn\'t. Why not? Well, what\'s the government\'s role in it? Unlike Nuclear weapons, it\'s not a commercial enterprise.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Computing, is a commercial enterprise and still get what the government needed. If you\'re going to stop testing, you have to do computing, but that has to be big computing. They were able to figure out they can make a dollar out of this sort of thing for a while. But I think you get a reputation being able to kind of tell it how it is to some degree. And you can see things the same way—if I could go back—the same way when I met Wally Wurster that this guy could see what a molecule, what a electronic F number—he had a feeling for what this is all about. And I have a feeling for how systems played—simple systems. So I didn\'t know Feynman, but I did know people who knew Feynman. I\'ve got a sense of seeing it and I don\'t try to push it further than that.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Mm-hmm.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>So there\'s a fair amount of luck involved, right? I mean, there just is. It\'s random, right? I mean, it\'s the pandemic, right? You bump into people, they\'re sick, you get it. But after I finish the book, I might be able to answer that a little—\'cause that\'s one of the questions is, well, how come—why did this happen?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah. Well, until then, it\'s been really terrific to talk to you. And I think, as a historical record, having this interview alongside with the memoir is just going to be a tremendous resource for researchers coming at this from so many different fields. So it\'s a—</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Oh, thank you. That\'s what I hope for.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And I\'m just hoping that I will be able to—you know, I\'m 85—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>I\'m sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>—I\'m hoping to be able to get it done.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>You\'ll get it done.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Yeah, I think so.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>You\'ll get it done.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And what happens is that, as you\'re looking back, things are not always the way they seemed at the time.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>That\'s right, that\'s right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Some people who do things, you say, "Boy, that\'s stupid." Well, maybe it wasn\'t so stupid. Or some people who do things that are smart.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right, right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And just \'cause you\'re a physicist—I mean, this was Eisenhower, right?</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Oh, yeah.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>Wait a minute, just \'cause this guy really understands—I mean, Teller was really a very good scientist I guess, but that doesn\'t give him an—</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>And you can check off some of the people that you\'ve worked with. But it is important.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>That\'s right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>All right? And how that interacts, you have to be able to see it, and sometimes I could see it. And, as I\'m looking back, sometimes I didn\'t see it.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>The forces were not aligned properly.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right, right. All right.</p>\n<h3>Reis:</h3>\n<p>That\'s strategic astrology.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>I\'m going to cut it here.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n'}